Analyze the categorized concern sets to identify explicit intersections. This involves finding concerns where patient and caregiver express the same core issue (e.g., both worried about medication side effects). The output is a list of aligned concerns with evidence from both data sets.

Analyze the categorized concern sets to identify explicit divergences. This involves finding concerns expressed by one party but not the other, or where the same topic is framed with opposing priorities/valence (e.g., patient fears loss of independence, caregiver fears safety risks). The output is a list of unique or conflicting concerns.

Examine how the expression, priority, or nature of concerns (both intersecting and divergent) vary across different contexts. Key contexts include disease stage, care setting (home vs. hospital), cultural background, and relationship dynamics. This identifies patterns where concerns are not static but shift based on situational factors.

Integrate the findings from intersection, divergence, and variation analyses into a coherent map or model. Compute proportional relationships between media components and textual content using appropriate metrics (e.g., media count vs. text volume, media area/space vs. text area/space, media file size vs. text character count).
Compile the extracted metadata and calculated ratios into a structured report showing media density distribution, highlighting areas of high/low media concentration relative to textual content.
Detect and record positional data for call-to-action elements within the content structure
Analyze the content structure to recognize common call-to-action element types (buttons, links, forms, banners) and their visual/contextual patterns within the layout.
Scan the rendered content to find the precise DOM nodes or visual regions containing call-to-action elements using selectors, visual detection, or structural analysis.
For each located CTA element, capture its positional data including viewport coordinates (x, y), bounding rectangle dimensions (width, height), and relative positioning within the content hierarchy.
Store the collected positional data along with associated CTA metadata (type, text content, target URL/action) in a structured format for analysis or reporting.
Perform statistical analysis to identify deviations between draft content metrics and historical engagement benchmarks.
Extract quantitative metrics (e.g., word count, sentiment score, keyword density) from the draft content.
Access stored historical data containing engagement metrics (e.g., CTR, dwell time, conversion rates) for comparable content.
Apply statistical methods (e.g., z-score, chi-square) to compare draft metrics against historical benchmarks and identify significant deviations.
Compile analysis results into a structured report highlighting key deviations and their statistical significance.
Evaluate comparison results against predefined performance thresholds to determine readiness for finalization.
Establish measurable key performance indicators to track engagement, campaign effectiveness, and health outcomes, integrating tracking tools.
